def find_integers(A, B, X):
    return [str(n) for n in range(1, X + 1) if B % n == 0 and n % A == 0]
integers = find_integers(*[int(i) for i in input().split()])
print (" ".join(integers) if len(integers)!=0 else "None")

Your solution should use a StringBuilder to build the result string. Concatenation via "+" will become slower and slower for longer strings.

When we have 3 by 7 = 21, 3 and 7 are call factors. and 21 is the multiple of 7 and 3

you must say: 
- {{A}} is a multiple of {{n}}, or
- {{n}} is a factor of {{A}}
According to the Wikipedia page, the terms "factor" and "divisor" refer to the same thing: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisor
it is intentional so that we can have B > A
Agree on both points and suggest changing to "B is divisible by n and n is divisible by A". Setter could also include the mathematical notation, B | n and n | A.

B>A may be the case even if they are both in the same interval.
To me it seems a distraction, since the purpose does not seem very clear.
Nice problem though overall!
